5. Object-Oriented Design
The system follows Object-Oriented Programming principles to ensure modularity, reusability, and maintainability.
Key OOP Principles Applied
•	Inheritance: Student and Faculty classes inherit from the abstract User class
•	Abstraction: Implemented using the abstract User class and the PerformanceTracker interface
•	Encapsulation: Class attributes are private and accessed through getters and setters
•	Polymorphism: Methods such as login(), displayInfo(), and logout() are overridden in subclasses
Main System Classes
•	User (Abstract Class): Contains shared attributes such as username, password, and role
•	Student: Handles GPA calculation, attendance management, and student-specific data
•	Faculty: Manages grades, assessments, and student performance
•	Course: Stores course information and enrolled students
•	Enrollment: Links students with courses and records grades and semesters
•	AlertManager: Generates attendance alerts and performance notifications
•	DAO Classes: StudentDAO, AttendanceDAO, and EnrollmentDAO handle database operations
•	DBConnection: Manages JDBC connection with SQL Server
________________________________________
6. Database Design
The system uses SQL Server to store academic and user data securely.
Database Tables
Users
•	UserID (Primary Key)
•	Username
•	Password
•	Role (Student / Faculty)
Students
•	StudentID (Primary Key, Foreign Key to Users)
•	Name
•	Major
•	GPA
•	TotalHours
Faculty
•	FacultyID (Primary Key, Foreign Key to Users)
•	Name
•	Department
Courses
•	CourseID (Primary Key)
•	CourseCode
•	CourseName
•	CreditHours
Enrollments
•	EnrollmentID (Primary Key)
•	StudentID (Foreign Key)
•	CourseID (Foreign Key)
•	Semester
•	GradeType
•	Score
•	Year
Attendance
•	AttendanceID (Primary Key)
•	StudentID (Foreign Key)
•	TotalDays
•	AttendedDays
Entity Relationships
•	Users → Students / Faculty (1:1)
•	Students → Enrollments (1:N)
•	Courses → Enrollments (1:N)
•	Students → Attendance (1:1)
________________________________________
7. JDBC and DAO Integration
The system connects Java with SQL Server using JDBC.
The DBConnection class establishes and manages the database connection.
DAO classes are responsible for:
•	Validating user login credentials
•	Retrieving student and course data using SQL queries
•	Fetching grades and calculating GPA
•	Calculating attendance percentages and generating alerts
This approach ensures separation of concerns, improves maintainability, and enhances system scalability.
